  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Clothing assistance for displaced persons in camp settings in Ninewa and Kirkuk</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">This project aims to provide immediate support to IDPs in camp contexts in eastern Ninewa Governorate and Kirkuk Governorate through the provision of clothing items in priority locations where IDPs are unable to leave the camp setting and access markets. IDPs from Mosul and Hawiga have fled with very little if any NFIs and often arriving at the screening centres with just the single set of clothes that they were wearing at the time. Provision of clothing is therefore a key need to reduce the resulting health and protection risks, particularly in the camp context where households are in basic conditions, and are confined within the camp. 

The distribution of clothing is in line with the second line response strategy outlined in the Shelter and NFI guidance for this allocation and in the 2017 HRP, procuring and distributing standardized, seasonally - appropriate clothing kits in priority locations. This action follows the sequenced response process of assistance packages per the HRP strategy.

Clothing will be distributing using a voucher shop methodology that Tearfund has been a leading actor in piloting and expanding coverage of during the Mosul Response to date, covering over 16,000 individuals with winter clothing between November 2016 and January 2017. This approach enables beneficiaries a high degree of choice and freedom in selecting clothing items appropriate and most needed within their specific household, up to the value of the voucher, which can be adjusted according to family size.</narrative>
  </description>
